0.body: We will follow a lecture format with live demonstrations. I strongly encourage you to participate actively by replicating each demo as it is presented. Note: Feel free to ask questions at the end of each section. If you need clarification or further information on any topic discussed, don’t hesitate to speak up. Note: Given the extensive amount of concepts to cover during these three hours, it is highly recommended that you thoroughly review the notes before the next hands-on session.

27.body: Despite the seal being relatively simple looking, we are going to model it in a particular way in order to modifiers to apply correctly and later textures in our next session. Adding a circle Shortcut Method: In Object Mode, with face select on Shift+A. Position into place with g and locking to axis x, y or z Extrude, Exit, Scale Move Shortcut Method: In Edit Mode, with all edges selected 2 for edge select. We do a combo move e, esc, s the extrude creates a new edge, escape cancels the extrusion operation, s scales the newly created edge. Grid filling the centre Shortcut Method: In Face menu, we will grid fill the centre. Applying the Shrink Wrap Modifier Shortcut Method: In Object Mode, we navigate to the modifiers tab and add a new deformation modifier called shrinkwrap with the target being our bottle. We will then apply the modifier permanently. Extruding Shortcut Method: In Edit Mode, with all faces selected we eextrude.

GUI Note: In Blender, you can open File > External Data > Find Missing Files if you need to relocate downloaded textures. 5.body: Below are several essential concepts we’ll use throughout this booklet. Each concept highlights shortcuts and the corresponding menu paths. Subdivision Modeling Shortcut Method: In Object Mode, press Ctrl+2 (or Ctrl+1, Ctrl+3, etc.) to automatically add a Subdivision Surface Modifier with a chosen subdivision level. GUI Method: Select your object, then go to Properties > Modifiers > Add Modifier > Subdivision Surface. Solidify Modifier Shortcut Method: There’s no direct one-key shortcut to add a Solidify Modifier. However, you can quickly open the Add Modifier menu by pressing Ctrl+Tab in newer Blender versions (if configured) or simply do the next step: GUI Method: Select your object, go to Properties > Modifiers > Add Modifier > Solidify, then adjust the Thickness. Displacement Modifier Shortcut Method: Similarly, no default direct shortcut. Recommended approach is to use Shift+A in the Texture context to quickly add a texture, then reference it in the Displace Modifier. GUI Method: With your object selected, go to Properties > Modifiers > Add Modifier > Displace. Assign or create a new texture under Texture > New. Shrinkwrap Modifier Shortcut Method: No direct key. Add via quick menu F3 to open the search bar, type Shrinkwrap. GUI Method: Select your object, then choose Properties > Modifiers > Add Modifier > Shrinkwrap. Pick the target object to wrap onto. Modifier Application Shortcut Method: Select the object, press F3, type Apply All Modifiers. GUI Method: Go to Properties > Modifiers and click the Apply button on each modifier. Mesh Cleanup Shortcut Method: In Edit Mode, press F3 and type Merge by Distance or Delete Loose or Limited Dissolve. GUI Method: In Edit Mode, go to Mesh > Clean Up and choose the required cleanup operation. Activating and Utilizing Add-ons Shortcut Method: In newer Blender versions, press F4, choose Preferences, and go to the Add-ons tab. GUI Method: Go to Edit > Preferences > Add-ons. Check the box next to the desired add-on. Use of Proportional Editing Shortcut Method: In Edit Mode, press O to toggle Proportional Editing on/off. Scroll the Mouse Wheel to adjust the falloff radius while transforming. GUI Method: In Edit Mode, enable Proportional Editing by clicking the small circle icon on the 3D Viewport header. Creating and Modifying Curves Shortcut Method: Press Shift+A and select Curve > Bezier (or Curve > NURBS). To modify, press Tab to enter Edit Mode, and use G (move), R (rotate), S (scale). GUI Method: Go to Add > Curve > Bezier/NURBS. Then switch to Edit Mode via Object > Mode > Edit Mode.
